As Todd wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/21/2004 at 03:43:22 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>Dear Dr. Math,
>
>A co-worker and I were at Starbuck's the other day and he ordered a 
>tall (12 oz) no foam latte, but was given one with about an inch of 
>foam.
>
>We then got into a debate of how you would use math to compute the 
>profit Starbucks was gaining by putting foam in the cup. Aside from 
>the nominal amount of material in the foam, let's assume it accounts 
>for empty space for the sake of argument.
>
>We know the radius of the top and bottom of the cup, along with the 
>height and the volume when full (12 oz). The debate was this - one 
>person said you would have to measure two cones and deduct the 
>volumes to find out how much material was missing. 
>
>The other (who has not had a calculus class in an embarassingly long 
>time) remembered vaguely that you should be able to take the partial 
>derivative of the volume of the cone, with respect to h, and compute 
>both the height of the cone when extended beyond the bottom of the 
>cup, and the reduction in volume when lowering the contents.
>
>I thought this an interesting problem, so please don't waste your 
>time if you find it useless.
>
>Thanks!
>
>-Todd 
>
>[Difficulty]
>The radius should be decreasing as height decreases, however the 
>problem seems more complicated and developing an equation to 
represent
>the relationship with a known volume and two known radius' is beyond 
>my knowledge.
>
>[Thoughts]
>V = 1/3 * PI * R^2 * H
>
>Seems like we should know R at different points if we were to graph 
>the volumes where the x-axis would be H and the y-axis is V.
>
>Because we know that between two points where we already have R and 
>(H2 - H1) and V, there would be a formula for deriving the total 
>value of H and subsequently, the volume at H - 1. 

